00:00:00,350 --> 00:00:03,350
In this video we are going to learn skills.

2
00:00:03,350 --> 00:00:09,590
Design pattern skills is one of the important pattern when querying between microservices.

3
00:00:09,860 --> 00:00:17,030
We can use skills design pattern in order to avoid complex queries to get rid of the inefficient joins.

4
00:00:17,480 --> 00:00:22,040
Queries stands for the command and query Responsibility segregation.

5
00:00:22,130 --> 00:00:28,040
And basically this pattern separates read and write operations with separating the databases.

6
00:00:28,790 --> 00:00:34,160
The main idea is that we can divide application operations into two separate categories.

7
00:00:34,160 --> 00:00:35,690
The first one is commands.

8
00:00:35,690 --> 00:00:41,600
These commands are changing the state of data into application, and the second one is queries.

9
00:00:41,810 --> 00:00:44,780
And these queries are handling the complex.

10
00:00:44,780 --> 00:00:50,600
Join operations and returning a result and don't change the state of data into the application.

11
00:00:51,560 --> 00:00:57,950
In a large scale, microservice architectures need to manage high volume data requirements for this

12
00:00:57,950 --> 00:00:59,150
kind of use cases.

13
00:00:59,150 --> 00:01:06,200
Monolithic approach, like single databases for services, can cause the bottlenecks for complex and

14
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:08,120
large scale microservice architectures.

15
00:01:08,120 --> 00:01:14,210
We can use both skills and event sourcing pattern in order to improve application performance.

16
00:01:14,210 --> 00:01:21,620
Skills offers to separate the read and write data that provide to maximize query performance and scalability.

17
00:01:23,340 --> 00:01:25,740
Let's think about the monolithic applications.

18
00:01:25,740 --> 00:01:32,610
Most of the time we have one database, and this database should respond to both query and update operations.

19
00:01:32,700 --> 00:01:39,630
That means a single database is both working for the complex joint queries and also perform Crud operations.

20
00:01:40,440 --> 00:01:47,280
But if the application goes more complex, this query and Crud operations will be also is going to be

21
00:01:47,280 --> 00:01:48,840
unmanageable situation.

22
00:01:49,350 --> 00:01:55,680
In example of reading database, if your application required some queries that needs to join more than

23
00:01:55,680 --> 00:02:01,050
one table that will lock the database due to latency of query computation.

24
00:02:01,560 --> 00:02:07,770
Also, if we give example of writing database when performing Crud operations, we would need to make

25
00:02:07,770 --> 00:02:11,190
complex validations and process long business logics.

26
00:02:11,190 --> 00:02:14,580
So this will cause to lock the database operations also.

27
00:02:15,150 --> 00:02:21,090
So reading and writing database has different approaches that we can define different strategies in

28
00:02:21,090 --> 00:02:22,860
order to handle that operations.

29
00:02:23,460 --> 00:02:30,090
In order to do that, Sickles offer to use separation of concerns principles and separate reading database

30
00:02:30,090 --> 00:02:32,970
and writing database with two databases.

31
00:02:32,970 --> 00:02:39,420
By this way, we can even use different database for reading and writing database types, like using

32
00:02:39,420 --> 00:02:45,960
NoSQL databases for reading operations and using relational databases for Crud operations.

33
00:02:46,410 --> 00:02:53,730
Mostly read database uses NoSQL database with denormalized data which is generated from the right database,

34
00:02:53,730 --> 00:03:01,110
and right database uses relational databases with fully normalized and support strong data consistency.

35
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:07,980
But during this section we are going to use logical sequence pattern implementation, which separates

36
00:03:07,980 --> 00:03:11,880
the read and write operations logically in ordering microservices.

